SIMPLE: exasperate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exasperate
<hw>Ex*as"per*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>exasperatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>exsasperare</ets> to roughen,
exasperate; <ets>ex</ets> out (intens.) + <ets>asperare</ets> to make
rough, <ets>asper</ets> rough. See <er>Asperity</er>.]</ety>
<def>Exasperated; imbittered.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like swallows which the <qex>exasperate</qex> dying year⟦br⟧
Sets spinning.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exasperate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Exasperate
<hw>Ex*as"per*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Exsasperated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Exasperating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To irritate in a high degree; to provoke; to enrage; to
excite or to inflame the anger of; <as>as, to <ex>exasperate</ex> a
person or his feelings</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>exsasperate</qex> them against the king of France.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make grievous, or more grievous or malignant; to
aggravate; to imbitter; <as>as, to <ex>exasperate</ex>
enmity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>exasperate</qex> the ways of death.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Browne.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To irritate; provoke. See
<er>Irritate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exasperater</ent>⟦br⟧
